Helped build the Phantom Ship — the New Haven vessel whose loss in 1647 took Thomas Gregson and other leading citizens. His name is memorialized on Founder's Bridge over the Wepawaug River in Milford, CT.","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":7,"category":"immigration","header":"He refused the King’s ship money","body":"The 1636 Hertfordshire arrears roll lists Richard Miles of Wormley among those who would not pay Charles I’s ship-money tax — with the notation “gone into New England.” He landed at Boston the next summer with Rev. Peter Prudden’s Hertfordshire company."},{"number":8,"category":"maritime","header":"He helped build the phantom ship","body":"Governor Eaton entrusted Miles and others with constructing New Haven’s great ship of 1646 — the ill-built vessel that sailed into the Atlantic and was never seen again. Among the lost was Thomas Gregson, whose daughter later married into Hartford’s Whiting family."},{"number":9,"category":"politics","header":"One of Milford’s forty-four free planters","body":"At Milford’s first General Court in November 1639, forty-four church members were granted the franchise as “free planters,” Miles among them. A 1641 New Haven schedule shows him heading a household of seven on four hundred acres."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Richard Miles","notes":"Also spelled \"Myles\" in early records. Parents: Rychard and Alice Cherrye Myles.","first_name":"Richard","last_name":"Miles","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Magistrate and Deputy","organization":"New Haven Colony"},{"role":"Selectman","organization":"New Haven","start_year":1651,"end_year":1652},{"role":"Clerk of Artillery","organization":"New Haven","start_year":1648}],"slug":"richard-miles-1598"},"X01844":{"id":"X01844","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{